cs.RO, cs.AI, cs.LG, cs.CV, cs.SY

Reasoning: 
1. cs.RO (Robotics): The paper focuses on dynamic stair climbing with a humanoid robot, and proposes a walking stabilization method based on linear inverted pendulum tracking, wrench distribution, and whole-body admittance control. This is a clear indication that the paper belongs to the Robotics sub-category.
2. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence): The paper proposes a novel walking stabilization method that combines two existing approaches to improve tracking performance. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence sub-category.
3. cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper does not explicitly mention the use of machine learning techniques, but the proposed walking stabilization method involves optimization using quadratic programming. This could be considered a form of machine learning, and hence the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning sub-category.
4. cs.CV (Computer Vision): The paper does not involve any computer vision techniques, but the HRP-4 humanoid robot is equipped with cameras and sensors for perception and navigation. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Computer Vision sub-category.
5. cs.SY (Systems and Control): The paper proposes a walking stabilization method that involves both end-effector and CoM strategies, and uses whole-body admittance control. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control sub-category.
